list-item.p:
Depending on the coverage (Photos 1, 2):
partially covered self-expandable stents – e.g. Ultraflex, Esopha-Coil, Flamingo, Gianturco Z-stent, Evolution;
fully covered self-expandable stents – e.g. Alimaxx-E, Niti-S, SX-Ella, Wallflex, Polyflex.

Depending on the material used:
nitinol – e.g. Ultraflex, Esopha-Coil, Wallflex, Niti-S, Choo, Hanaroo, Evolution, Alimaxx-E;
steel – e.g. Gianturco Z-stent, Flamingo, Wallstent II;
plastic – e.g. Polyflex.
polydioxanone – e.g. Ella (Photo 3).

Depending on function:
with an anti-reflux valve – e.g. Ella, Dostent;
with an anti-migration mechanisms – e.g. Alimaxx.

Depending on release:
distal – e.g. Ultraflex;
proximal – e.g. Ultraflex.

sec.p:
The main indications for palliative oesophageal stenting include:
dysphagia due to the inoperable oesophageal cancer;
oesophageal compression due to mediastinal diseases (Hodgkin's disease, non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, inoperable lung cancer);
small cell lung cancer infiltrating the oesophagus;
thyroid cancer.

Generally, three methods of dilatation can be distinguished [16]:
mercury-filled rubber dilators – e.g. Maloney or Hurst;
guided polyvinyl dilators – e.g. Savary-Gilliard, Eder-Puestow, Celestin, Beuss, Biomed System American;
hydrostatic polyurethane balloons – e.g. TTS (through-the-scope), Rigiflex, Medi-Tech.

The ideal prosthesis should have the following characteristics:
appropriate diameter enabling full oral nutrition without obstruction after meals;
low risk of migration, granulation tissue stent overgrowth, bleeding, and fistula formation;
flexibility;
technical simplicity of implantation, reposition, and removal;
low risk of regurgitation.
